title: [validator] Refactor validator to ES6 import/export module style
body:
# Improvement to existing type definition.
- Refactor `validator.d.ts` and enable to `validator` can **import that default export by omitting the curly braces** and **import only a subset of the library**.

Example:

```
import validator from 'validator';
import { blacklist, contains } from 'validator';
```
- Besides keeping original API test cases, it adds import tests.

---

I found this definition, it can't import like [validator document](https://github.com/chriso/validator.js#es6) describe.

It's because of invoking `export =` in the original definition, it won't export more any modules. It blocks `validator` has real ES6 module feature.

Therefore, I send this PR after I refactor a new file as `validator-es6-tests.ts`. I want to invite validator authors to review this, and not cover the original definition. When this PR get prove, I hope it will be the formal definition next PR.

If validator authors have any questions, please let me know. Thanks.

``` ts
import * as validator from 'validator';

console.log(validator.normalizeEmail('gOI@NF.cc'))

```

outputs:

```
false
false
goi@nf.cc
boolean
boolean
string
```

---
# TypeScript-STL v1.1
## New Features
#### [std.for_each_n](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/modules/std.html#for_each_n)
- New feature of C++17
#### [std.base.UniqueMap.extract](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniquemap.html#extract)
- New feature of C++17.
- Extract an element ([Pair](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.pair.html)) from a UniqueMap container.
- Removes an element from a UniqueMap and returns the elemnet.
#### [std.base.UniqueMap.insert_or_assign](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniquemap.html#insert_or_assign)
- New feature of C++17
- Find matched key. If exists, change the mapped value. If not, then inserts the new element.
- It's same with the [base.UniqueMap.set()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniquemap.html#set). I have predicted that such function will be added in C++17, however, failed to predict its name.
#### [std.base.UniqueMap.emplace](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniquemap.html#emplace)

In C+\+ STL, _emplace()_ is a method who calls _insert()_ with _new T object_, constructed from arguments of varadic template in the emplace(). Using paraeterms in emplace() to creating a new T object, it's possible because the characteristics of C++ template system. Implementing it is not possible in the JavaScript.

However, the map containers, they are storing elements with capsulizing key and mapped value into a std.Pair object. It means that the map containers, their value type is specified exactly (as std.Pair). Thus only the map containers, realizing emplace() is feasible.

``` cpp
template <typename T, typename Alloc = std::allocator<T>, typename Compare = std::less<T>> 
class unordered_set
{
public:
    template <typename ...Args>
    void emplace(Args&&... args)
    {
        // VARADIC TEMPLATE, IT'S ONLY POSSIBLE IN C++
        T &element(args...);
        insert(element);
    }
}
```
#### [std.base.MultiMap.emplace](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.multimap.html#emplace)
- Same with the std.base.UniqueMap.emplace
#### [std.base.MapContainer.emplace_hint](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.mapcontainer.html#emplace_hint)
- Same with the std.base.UniqueMap.emplace
#### [std.base.UniqueSet.extract](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniqueset.html#extract)
- Same with the std.base.UniqueMap.extract
#### [std.base.UniqueSet.insert_or_assign](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniqueset.html#insert_or_assign)
- Same with the std.base.UniqueMap.insert_or_assign
## Fixed Errors
#### [std.Vector.iterator.advance](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.vectoriterator.html#advance)
- Calling advance() with minus value had ignored.
- When the iterator is pointing to the [Vector.end()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.vector.html#end).
#### [std.Deque.iterator.advance](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.dequeiterator.html#advance)
- Same with the std.Vector.iterator.advance
#### [std.Deque.erase](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.deque.html#erase)
- There had been an error that a Deque is being locked.
- When only an element was existed in a Deque and the last element is deleted, the last row in the matrix (who is storing Deque's elements in) is also deleted. Thus any row exists in the matrix and it causes any element can be inserted into the Deque.
#### [std.reverse](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/modules/std.html#reverse)
- It had not worked at all.
## Refactoring
#### Sorting algorithm on the [std.List.sort()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.list.html#sort) has changed.

Until before, [std.sort()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/modules/std.html#sort) had subrogated the std.List.sort().
- Elements in std.List are copied into a new std.Vector
- After sorting via std.sort(), elements in the std.Vector are assigned the the std.List.

``` typescript
class List<T>
{
    public sort(): void
    {
        // UNTIL BEFORE, STD.SORT HAD SUBROGATED
        let vector: Vector<T> = new Vector<T>(this.begin(), this.end());
        std.sort(vector.begin(), vector.end());

        this.assign(vector.begin(), vector.end());
    }
}
```

From now on, the sorting is done by std.List itself.
#### Protected methods are renamed.
- Some methods, they can't avoid to be protected accessor type in domain reason.
  - They're all derived from [std.base.MapContainer](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.mapcontainer.html) and many methods of them are protected methods.
    - [std.base.UniqueMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniquemap.html)
      - [std.TreeMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.treemap.html)
      - [std.HashMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.hashmap.html)
    - [std.base.MultiMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.multimap.html)
      - [std.TreeMultiMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.treemultimap.html)
      - [std.HashMultiMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.hashmultimap.html)
- The protected members, they can be accessed by subclasses and it may cause critical error.
- The best way is to changing them to be private, but it's impossible. Instead, I renamed them start from capital letter and have prefix underscore (**_**).
  - `std.base.SetContainer.handle_insaert` -> [std.base.SetContainer._Handle_insert](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.setcontainer.html#_handle_insert)
  - `std.base.MapContainer.insert_by_hint` -> `std.base.MapContainer._Insert_by_hint`

- Calling advance() with minus value had ignored.
- When the iterator is pointing to the [Vector.end()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.vector.html#end).
#### [std.Deque.iterator.advance](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.dequeiterator.html#advance)
- Same with the std.Vector.iterator.advance
#### [std.Deque.erase](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.deque.html#erase)
- There had been an error that a Deque is being locked.
- When only an element was existed in a Deque and the last element is deleted, the last row in the matrix (who is storing Deque's elements in) is also deleted. Thus any row exists in the matrix and it causes any element can be inserted into the Deque.
#### [std.reverse](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/modules/std.html#reverse)
- It had not worked at all.
## Refactoring
#### Sorting algorithm on the [std.List.sort()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.list.html#sort) has changed.

Until before, [std.sort()](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/modules/std.html#sort) had subrogated the std.List.sort().
- Elements in std.List are copied into a new std.Vector
- After sorting via std.sort(), elements in the std.Vector are assigned the the std.List.

``` typescript
class List<T>
{
    public sort(): void
    {
        // UNTIL BEFORE, STD.SORT HAD SUBROGATED
        let vector: Vector<T> = new Vector<T>(this.begin(), this.end());
        std.sort(vector.begin(), vector.end());

        this.assign(vector.begin(), vector.end());
    }
}
```

From now on, the sorting is done by std.List itself.
#### Protected methods are renamed.
- Some methods, they can't avoid to be protected accessor type in domain reason.
  - They're all derived from [std.base.MapContainer](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.mapcontainer.html) and many methods of them are protected methods.
    - [std.base.UniqueMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.uniquemap.html)
      - [std.TreeMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.treemap.html)
      - [std.HashMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.hashmap.html)
    - [std.base.MultiMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.multimap.html)
      - [std.TreeMultiMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.treemultimap.html)
      - [std.HashMultiMap](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.hashmultimap.html)
- The protected members, they can be accessed by subclasses and it may cause critical error.
- The best way is to changing them to be private, but it's impossible. Instead, I renamed them start from capital letter and have prefix underscore (**_**).
  - `std.base.SetContainer.handle_insaert` -> [std.base.SetContainer._Handle_insert](http://samchon.github.io/typescript-stl/api/classes/std.base.setcontainer.html#_handle_insert)
  - `std.base.MapContainer.insert_by_hint` -> `std.base.MapContainer._Insert_by_hint`
